been compared to Elvis Costello, but I think Huey has a far more bitter, 
cynical sense of humor.

practiced by a society.   Normal in physical context, is any traits that 
are common enough to not curve into two standard deviations beyond a set 
percentage.  1 in 100 people have aspergers. That means people with

I still remember watching this on vhs approximately 27 years ago. Although, 
they had released an alternative version out to the public. I feel so 
relieved. Finally, everyone will be able witness the true story being 
unfold and having light shed on this event after so many years of it being 
swept under the rug and covered up with dishonesty. Well yes, now, you 
know.This was actually cut from the original live recording due to the 
horrific nature of its content and producers being under a lot of heat from 
the audience for allowing the clip to be broadcasted. (It was removed 
immediately just hours after airing.) Having taken a lot of criticism and 
numerous amount of death threats, the director's image as a professional 
and visual artist was now being torn apart. His personality completely 
shifted that day. The kind, friendly man the community once knew had 
disappeared. It was as if he was being possessed by some sort of foul 
demonic creature you'd only hear about in an old folk tale or mythological 
legend. He became cold-hearted and mentally illed. The video became an 
obsession. It consumed him. Before being taken away to an insane asylum, he 
was able to create a single copy which he locked away in the Comedy 
Central(CC) vault up until this day. Which was willed to his son before 
passing away in 2014. Now, not a lot of people are aware of this and it 
might creep you the hell out, but I am hopeful that we as a society are 
mature enough to handle the following words I'm about to write. The 
director's mind was not completely lost like they said in the file reports. 
At the end of the clip, you'd noticed how it ended abruptly. It felt like a 
second too early, right? What you don't know is that there were about 2 
minutes of extra footage left behind from the director after everyone ran 
off the set. As he stood, his eyes stared blankly into the lens as he held 
the final note card up towards the camera. I'm afraid i'm not allowed to 
reveal the last sentence of his message for it would jeopardize everything 
and everyone I care about. I apologize. Now, you may be wondering..how can 
I know all this information? Well, you see... It's because

I am the son.ï»¿

For anyone wondering, this is indeed loosely based on a real story. You may 
recall raywilliamjohnson reviewed a video about the 1987 Crystal Light 
National Aerobic Championships. The music in this video is actually the 
music that plays in that video. It was a big event hosted by Alan Thicke. 
Anyway, in that championship, one of the competitors learned a family 
member, (I'm not sure exactly what type of family member,) was in an 
accident, presumably a car crash. However, the competitor learned this 
offstage and didn't attack the other competitors. This video was just made 
as a dark twist on that event. So if you want to know the true story, here 
it is.ï»¿

As a gay man, I found this funny yet insulting. I'm all for having a good 
laugh but when it's something along the lines of this video, it puts gay 
men down. Was his behavior work place appreciate? No. But I can recall 
countless times of straight male coworkers giving explicit details of their 
sexual activity and their bodies. Personally, this kind of subject matter 
does not bother me at all. I'm a very open minded person and not much 
(anything that is consensual between persons that are of legal age and 
sound mind) bothers me when someone goes on about their sexual endeavors. 
Of course this is a satire but it does suggest that gay men should present 
themselves as "non flamboyant" or "straight suggestive" because being open 
about your sexuality could be taken as "pushing your lifestyle down 
someone's throat." Again, I like to mention that although this wasn't 
literally said, it suggests that being an openly gay man(who's flamboyant) 
makes them an asshole due to their openness possibly being taken as 
"shoving their lifestyle down someone's throat." This is not the kind of 
comedy the lgbt community needs right now due to the fact that we are not 
treated equally (along with anyone else who isn't a well off, straight, 
white male). It's just giving more fuel to people who don't treat others 
equally or think of others as lesser humans and continue their behavior. 
The behavior I'm speaking of is the kind of behavior that gets people 
harassed, bullied, tortured and often killed. If we lived in a society of 
humans that treated everyone equally and respected everyone equally this 
would be hilarious. Unfortunately, we do not live in that world. So this 
kind of satire is not appropriate and is not how the gay community should 
be viewed. All it does it allow for stigma to continue. It may seem as 
though this is an over reaction but small hidden things like this video put 
us in trouble for the long run. To closex I would just like to thank anyone 
who actually read this and give it some food for thought. I appreciate you 
taking the time to hear what I had to say.ï»¿

To all the comments saying "(Insert gay or straight) people aren't like 
(this), they're like (that)", positive stereotyping of your own group is no 
less ignorant than negative stereotyping of someone else's.

The truth is there are nice people and assholes all over the place.  There 
are plenty of straight people who express their ignorant dislike of 
homosexuals.  There are plenty of straight people who don't really care 
what other people do in their bedrooms in the first place.  There are 
plenty of straight people who support equality for homosexuals.  There are 
plenty of gay people who are flamboyant and obnoxious, those are the ones 
most people notice.  Then there are plenty of gay people who are just like 
anyone else, except gay.  Those are the ones people don't notice, and just 
assume are straight because it never came up.

No group of people are all the same.  As long as you keep trying to figure 
out what a group of people is like, you'll always be wrong about the 
majority of the people in that group.

Personally, I'm in the group of straight people who think gay people should 
not be discriminated against, but I also believe that sexuality should not 
be obnoxiously expressed in public or in the professional environment, and 
I'm sick of people who talk about penis all the time and call anyone who 
asks them to stop a homophobe.  If a guy was in a public place surrounded 
by children and talking about fucking his girlfriend in the ass, people 
would immediately try to quiet him and get him out of the area.  If a 
homosexual talks about fucking a guy in the ass in public surrounded by 
children, he can point fingers calling people homophobes and actually 
manage to stay there for a while.  Granted, there will probably be 
arguments, but most people would refrain from stopping him lest they be 
accused of hating gay people.

Kind of like when there's a rude black person in a restaurant; white people 
have to just sit there and endure it, or else be accused of being a racist; 
they have to wait for another black person to ask the person to shut the 
hell up.

This sort of reverse discrimination is taking place against pretty much any 
group of people that share a characteristic of the stereotypical american: 
A white, christian, straight male.  Obviously this image needs to change 
and people need to be equal, but oppressing other groups of people just to 
elevate yourself will never bring about equality.  Discrimination of any 
sort is still discrimination, there is no justification for it.ï»¿

Video Title: Key & Peele Super Bowl Special - Marshawn Lynch and Richard Sherman's Joint Press Conference
Comment:
I'm seeing a lot of "this wasn't funny" and "I didn't laugh". Key and Peele 
are known to be very metaphorical through their skits, bringing up several 
topics such as economic inequality, racial profiling and several other 
political matters. I think it's fair to say the two have constructed an 
easy outlet/platform for their opinions to be represented in a manner that 
isn't aggressively blatant and also allows for the viewer to create their 
own opinions based on their interpretation. That's the way I see the Key & 
Peele skits. For this particular one I see a press conference full of 
individuals sitting on the edge of their seats and lingering on every 
single word the two are conjuring up. I interpret it as how so many people 
in our culture and our society hold the words of the most talked about 
celebrity or figure, so closely, no matter how unrelated to them personally 
those words being spoken may be... But I could be totally wrong, it's an 
interpretation, one of many I'm sure. Seeing as these two are comedians, 
I'm not necessarily saying that for the message you should give up the 
laugh but I do think one can come out watching this with something 
gained... ï»¿

For those of you who don't understand this skit, It's pretty much making 
fun of the 'Modern Art" scene these days.

They were pretty much saying that no matter how stupid and ridiculous your 
artwork is, you can slap a couple of words or even a story behind it and 
SOMEONE is going buy into it and praise it for being so "deep" and 
"thought-provoking". I know this from personal experience, I used to attend 
an art college.

For example, there was a student in one of my art classes who did a 
performance piece in which he slammed a chair on the floor for 10 minutes 
straight. I kid you not, that was the only thing he did for 10 minutes. 
After he finished, the student said "I wanted to capture the vicious 
turmoil that rages in society today." My teacher along with the entire 
class erupted in applause.  I'm thinking to myself "Am I missing something 
here, all I saw was a chair being slammed continuously on the floor for 10 
straight minutes. Maybe I'm crazy."

Anyways, just thought I'd share that to anyone who was confused about this 
skit. Props to Key and Peele for doing this.ï»¿

Arguably a portrayal of an oppositional allusion  to T, S, Eliots Modernist 
masterpiece "The Waste Land", the experimental theatrical piece 
"Dicknanigans" is an avant-garde play regarding the implications of a 
dissolution of societal norms. 
Furthermore, "Dicknanigans"  not only portrays the primitive savageness 
that lies within us all but also the storminess and verisimilitude of 
passion. The divisiveness of the ephemeral progression of the play acts a 
metaphor to Shakespeare's "Measure for Measure" as the macabre, fleeting 
nature of life is examined. In addition, the references to both 
Shakespeare's and Eliots works are in fact a juxtaposition of how figures 
can contribute to the culture of Western Society and analyze the growing 
barrenness/fragmentation of it. The violence is a satirical observation of 
the growing restlessness of the millennial generation and is a 
comment about how both pain and progress go hand in hand within our world. 
The repetition of violence and "Dicknanigans" link violence, sexuality and 
passion with one another to bring long harbored internal strife within our 
society to the surface. The cognizance portrayed within this play is an 
abstract view on realism; said cognizance is a hard counter to the 
existential despair and nihilism within modern society and the exquisite 
eucatastrophe is a refreshing and long overdue conclusion on the human 
condition.ï»¿
